the Daily Critic. Family lived in Mexico City and were honored guests at Maximilian and Carlotta's court via Theodosia's uncle and aunt who served in the imperial household."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"work","header":"Confederate engineer turned imperial railway builder","body":"Charles served as a Confederate engineer in the Civil War, then took a senior post on the Imperial Mexican Railway under Emperor Maximilian. His wife's uncle and aunt were members of the imperial household, and the family were honored guests at Maximilian and Carlotta's court."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Sent his wife and children out under armed","body":"When the French army withdrew from Mexico in 1867 and Maximilian was left to his death, Charles arranged for his wife and five children to flee Mexico City under armed escort to a place of safety. He himself died shortly afterward — his widow returned to Washington with no fortune and took a clerk's job at the Patent Office to support the children."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Charles","middle_name":"Gratiot","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"suffix":"Sr.","display_name":"Charles Gratiot Talcott Sr."},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"charles-talcott-sr-1834"},"I00265":{"id":"I00265","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"gender":"female","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1840,"month":8,"day":20,"city":"Washington","state":"District of Columbia","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1925,"month":2,"day":4,"city":"Washington","state":"District of Columbia","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM141","plot_notes":"Oak Hill Cemetery, Washington DC."},"parents":{"father_id":"X02145","mother_id":"X02146","father_research_notes":"Robert Barton Barnard — see X02145.","mother_research_notes":"Sophia Cropley Barnard — see X02146."},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"T01839","date_year":1858,"date_month":10,"date_day":18,"location_state":"District of Columbia","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["T01869","T01870","T01871","T01872","T01873"],"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1867},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"X02498","date_year":1899,"date_month":10,"date_day":25,"location_city":"Washington","location_state":"District of Columbia","location_country":"United States","children_ids":[]}],"number_of_marriages":2,"tags":["civil_servant","mexico_residence","widow"],"sources":[{"short":"Findagrave"},{"short":"Talcott Genealogy","page":"Entry 1839 (as wife)"},{"short":"Washington Daily Critic Sept 22, 1875"},{"short":"United Register of Civil, Military and Naval Service 1875-1899"}],"career":[{"role":"Clerk / Copyist","organization":"U.S. Patent Office, Department of the Interior","start_year":1869,"end_year":1899,"notes":"Worked at the Patent Office for 30 years — 1869 to 1899. Per Geoffrey D. Austrian's 'Herman Hollerith: Forgotten Giant of Information Processing' (Columbia University Press, 1982): 'Theodosia was one of the first female career employees at the Patent Office, and her income kept her family, and that of her son-in-law, financially solvent during Hollerith's down periods.' She left the Patent Office in 1899, the same year she married Thomas Hambleton."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"The pretty and brilliant Miss Theo. Barnard","body":"Theodosia Barnard was remembered in 1870s Georgetown as 'the pretty and brilliant Miss Theo. Barnard,' the Daily Critic noted on her son's Annapolis admission. Her family's connection to Maximilian's imperial household took her to Mexico City, and her armed flight from the capital after the empire's fall became part of family lore."},{"number":2,"category":"work","header":"Thirty years a Patent Office clerk","body":"After Charles died in 1867 leaving her with five children and no fortune, Theodosia took a clerk position at the U.S. Patent Office where she remained from 1869 to 1899 — one of the first women career federal employees. Per Geoffrey Austrian's 1982 Hollerith biography, her income also helped sustain her son-in-law Herman Hollerith's family during his early lean years."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Theodosia","middle_name":"Lawrence","last_name":"Hambleton","maiden_name":"Barnard","married_names":["Talcott","Hambleton"],"nickname":"\"Thedie\"","display_name":"Theodosia Lawrence \"Thedie\" Barnard Hambleton"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"theodosia-barnard-1840"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}